      "id": 1,
      "text": "Nassau Village’s name traces back to the Dutch House of Nassau, once the namesake of Long Island itself.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        4
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassau_County%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The village’s streets echo New England influence, giving its buildings a distinctly Federal style orientation.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        13
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.livingplaces.com/NY/Rensselaer_County/Nassau_Village.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "A piano action factory established just outside Nassau Village supplied jobs for many local residents.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.livingplaces.com/NY/Rensselaer_County/Nassau_Village.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Originally part of two affluent farms, the land was never subdivided, preserving its rural character.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.livingplaces.com/NY/Rensselaer_County/Nassau_Village.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "On March 31, 2006, Nassau Village marked its 200th anniversary with grand celebrations.",
